TY  - JOUR
T1  - Enacting Competitive Wars: Competitive Activity, Language Games, and Market Consequences
AU  - Rindova, Violina P.
AU  - Becerra, Manuel
AU  - Contardo, Ianna
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.14497655
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.14497655
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 670
EP  - 686
VL  - 29
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Research in industrial/organization economics and strategic management defines ?competitive wars? as periods of intensified competitive activity, which tend to have negative performance consequences for the warring firms. Drawing on Wittgenstein's concept of ?language games,? we develop a model of competitive wars as a sociolinguistic process enacted through strategic actions, linguistic practices, and shifts in resource allocations. The model suggests that the war language game increases stakeholder involvement and enables the warring firms, oftentimes, to improve performance.
AB  - Research in industrial/organization economics and strategic management defines ?competitive wars? as periods of intensified competitive activity, which tend to have negative performance consequences for the warring firms. Drawing on Wittgenstein's concept of ?language games,? we develop a model of competitive wars as a sociolinguistic process enacted through strategic actions, linguistic practices, and shifts in resource allocations. The model suggests that the war language game increases stakeholder involvement and enables the warring firms, oftentimes, to improve performance.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.14497655
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.14497655
Y2  - 2026/04/24
