TY  - JOUR
T1  - Ownership and the Changing Employment Relationship: A Comment on Rousseau and Shperling
AU  - Zardkoohi, Asghar
AU  - Paetzold, Ramona L.
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.14497605
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.14497605
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 556
EP  - 562
VL  - 29
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article takes issue with four points raised by Professors Rousseau and Shperling in their 2003 paper, ?Pieces of the Action: Ownership and the Changing Employment Relationship.? First, the authors maintain that labor-force mobility depends significantly on whether workers have general aptitudes or firm-specific ones. Second, they take exception to the Professors' contention that labor mobility is increasing. Third, they dispute the notion that benefits associated with seniority play a key role in employee retention. And finally, they rebut the Professors' view that firms use seniority-based benefits to take advantage of workers.
AB  - The article takes issue with four points raised by Professors Rousseau and Shperling in their 2003 paper, ?Pieces of the Action: Ownership and the Changing Employment Relationship.? First, the authors maintain that labor-force mobility depends significantly on whether workers have general aptitudes or firm-specific ones. Second, they take exception to the Professors' contention that labor mobility is increasing. Third, they dispute the notion that benefits associated with seniority play a key role in employee retention. And finally, they rebut the Professors' view that firms use seniority-based benefits to take advantage of workers.
