TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Mickey Loses Face: Recontextualization, Semantic Fit, and the Semiotics of Foreignness
AU  - Brannen, Mary Yoko
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.14497613
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.14497613
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 593
EP  - 616
VL  - 29
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Foreignness is generally viewed as a liability for the multinational enterprise, negatively affecting strategic fit and the successful transfer of firm assets abroad. Using semiotics?the study of how language systems convey meaning?and the Walt Disney Company's experiences in internationalization, I develop the notion of semantic fit as a necessary complement to strategic fit and formalize a conceptual model of recontextualization?the process by which firm assets take on new meanings in distinct cultural environments.
AB  - Foreignness is generally viewed as a liability for the multinational enterprise, negatively affecting strategic fit and the successful transfer of firm assets abroad. Using semiotics?the study of how language systems convey meaning?and the Walt Disney Company's experiences in internationalization, I develop the notion of semantic fit as a necessary complement to strategic fit and formalize a conceptual model of recontextualization?the process by which firm assets take on new meanings in distinct cultural environments.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.14497613
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.14497613
Y2  - 2026/04/24
